Implement aria-current as an AOM Property

02
On this page
  1. Adding ariaCurrent for the CampSpots Homepage

The The aria-current property is used to tell Assistive Technology which page the user is currently on when it is included as an option in a menu or other collection of elements. Usually, we’d use the aria-current attribute in our HTML. But the AOM also supports working with ariaCurrent today, albeit behind a flag.

Either way, this would be a nice thing to add to the MegaNav as there are a lot of different pages where the user could navigate.

Let’s try using AOM to add ariaCurrent for the home page.

Adding ariaCurrent for the CampSpots Homepage

Open your editor to the header.js file. This is where our Home link (our site logo) and MegaNav component live.

// components/header.js
const Header = () => {
    return (
        <header id="header">
            <div id="header-nav">

                    <a href="#">Login</a>

}

To accomplish this task, we’ll import a couple of React hooks at the top of the file.

The useEffect hook allows us to do stuff when the page renders. useRef lets us move beyond React to work directly with the DOM element that gets rendered.

import React, {useEffect, useRef} from "react"

First, we’ll create a React ref to the homepage anchor tag.

Inside of the Header component code but above the return, create a new variable called linkRef that will be set to useRef(null).

const Header = () => {
  const linkRef = useRef(null)
  return ...

  return ...

This creates a new ref with an initial value of null that React will keep track of for us. To associate the anchor tag with the ref, we’ll add a ref attribute that is set to the linkRef we created above.

Here’s how our code changes look:

Now that we have a reference to the link we want to manipulate, we need to create the ability to do that when the page loads.

This is where useEffect comes in.

Above the return statement but below where we create the linkRef, stub out the call to useEffect. To ensure our logic only runs once, we will pass an empty array as the second parameter.

// components/header.js
const Header = () => {
	const linkRef = useRef(null)

	useEffect(() => {
	
	 }, [])

  return (
    <header id="header">
        ...
    </header>
  )
}

Within useEffect we want to see if the current path we are on is the root route.

Since we are doing this check on the client side, we can look at document.location.pathname. If we are at the root, we can set the linkRef’s ariaCurrent property to be page for our homepage link.

This is where we will set our AOM property. If our condition is met we will access that ref we created and set the ariaCurrent property to page.

Here’s what our changes look like all together:

// components/header.js
const Header = () => {
	const linkRef = useRef(null)
	
	useEffect(() => {
    if(document.location.pathname === "/") {
      linkRef.current.ariaCurrent = 'page'
    }
  }, [])

  return (
    <header id="header">
      <div id="header-nav">
          <div id="header-logo">
            <a href="/" className="header-main-item" ref={linkRef}>
						...

If you go to the browser and refresh, you’ll see the aria-current attribute reflected on the home page.

In the console, we can confirm that the property is set by querying for the element with querySelector and checking the property on the object.

We’ve confirmed that we set a property with AOM and it’s been reflected onto the HTML element as an attribute.

However, keep in mind that until full AOM support is adopted by Chrome & Firefox, this will only work for users who have enabled the AOM flags in their browser settings.
